    <teiHeader><fileDesc><titleStmt><title>The Ambassador in the Soviet Union (
                        Harriman
                    ) to the Secretary of
                            State</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1945v03</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d938</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">938</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1945-06-04T12:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1945-06-04T12:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-06-04T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-06-04T12:00:00-05:00" n="938" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d938">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">860C.014/6–445: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-06-04T20:00:00+03:00">June 4, 1945—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 8:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1890. In recent conversation with Maiski, Kennan pointed out that large portions
                    of Soviet Zone of occupation had been turned over to Warsaw Govt and questioned
                    the effect this might have on collection of reparations from this territory by
                    the Control Council. Maiski stated he did not think this a serious problem. He
                    drew attention to fact that Poland would be a reparations-receiving country and
                    implied that production of these areas could be credited to Poland’s share of
                    reparations from Germany.</p>
                <p>This is first indication we have had of Soviet views on this question.</p>
                <p>Sent Dept as 1890 rptd Paris for Murphy as 154.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
